{"id":"deaconess","term":"Deaconess","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p><a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Romans 16:1\">Rom. 16:1</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Romans 16:3\">3</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Romans 16:12\">12</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Philippians 4:2\">Phil. 4:2</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Philippians 4:3\">3</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"1 Timothy 3:11\">1 Tim. 3:11</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"1 Timothy 5:9\">5:9</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"1 Timothy 5:10\">10</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Titus 2:3\">Titus 2:3</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Titus 2:4\">4</a>). In these passages it is evident that females were then engaged in various Christian ministrations. Pliny makes mention of them also in his letter to Trajan (A.D. 110).</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Romans 16:1","Romans 16:3","Romans 16:12","Philippians 4:2","Philippians 4:3","1 Timothy 3:11","1 Timothy 5:9","1 Timothy 5:10","Titus 2:3","Titus 2:4"]}